<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">February 10, 2025</h2>
<a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hub-daily-february-10-2025/"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-249266 size-thumbnail" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/JavaScript_code-e1738962916104-150x150.png" alt="code" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li><a href="https://www.quantamagazine.org/the-poetry-fan-who-taught-an-llm-to-read-and-write-dna-20250205/?src=longreads" class="external" target="_blank">A computer scientist who loves poetry has created a genomic LLM to “help make sense of the genetic library</a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://nymag.com/intelligencer/article/pamela-paul-goodbye-to-the-new-york-times-opinion-columnist.html" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">Andrea Long Chu on Pamela Paul and reactionary liberalism</span></a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2025/02/07/the-image-of-the-doll-tove-ditlevsens-worn-out-language/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">The life and work of Danish poet Tove Ditlevsen</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> </span></li>
</ul>
